definition.value: A monocarboxylic acid that is 3-phenylpropionic acid in which the hydrogen at the para position of the phennyl group has been replaced by a nitro group.

An arenesulfonic acid that is 3-hydroxynaphthalene-2,7-disulfonic acid carrying a {2-sulfo-4-[(4-sulfophenyl)diazenyl]phenyl}diazenyl group at position 4. The tetrasodium salt is the biological stain 'Ponceau S'.
An organosulfonate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the sulfo groups of Ponceau S.
A non-proteinogenic alpha-amino acid that is homocysteine in which the thiol group has benn oxidised to the corresponding sulfonic acid.

A C85 alpha-mycolic acid produced by Mycobacterium tuberculosis having a C58 meromycolic chain with one cis cyclopropyl function, one methoxy function and one methyl subsituent, and a saturated C24 alpha-branch.
A dipeptide obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of L-serine with the amino group of L-isoleucine.
An N-acetyl-alpha-D-glucosaminide in which the anomeric hydroxy hydrogen is replaced by a 2-nitrophenyl group.
A dipeptide obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of L-threonine with the amino group of L-valine.
A member of the class of hydroxyindoles that is indoxyl carrying additional chloro and bromo substituents at positions 4 and 5 respectively.
A dipeptide obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of L-valine with the amino group of L-threonine.
An N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminide in which the anomeric hydroxy hydrogen is replaced by a 1-naphthyl group.
An N-acylglycine in which the N-acyl group is specified as indol-3-ylacetyl.
An alpha,beta-unsaturated monocarboxylic acid that is acrylic acid in which one of the hydrogens at position 3 is replaced by an indol-2-yl group.
An N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminide in which the anomeric hydroxy hydrogen is replaced by a 2-nitrophenyl group.
An anionic ganglioside obtained by deprotonation of the neuraminosyl carboxy group of III3FucVI3NeuAc-nLc6Cer; major species at pH 7.3.
An anionic ganglioside obtained by deprotonation of the neuraminosyl carboxy group of V3FucVI3NeuAc-nLc6Cer; major species at pH 7.3.
A glycolipid that consists of 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol having dodecanoyl as the acyl groups and an alpha-D-galactosyl-(1->6)-beta-D-galactosyl residue attached at position 3.
An indolyl carbohydrate that is the N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminide of indoxyl in which the indole moiety is substituted at positions 4 and 5 by chlorine and bromine, respectively.
An anionic ganglioside obtained by deprotonation of the neuraminosyl carboxy group of VI3NeuAc-nLc6Cer; major species at pH 7.3.
A 1,2-diacyl-3-beta-D-galactosyl-sn-glycerol in which the acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are specified as dodecanoyl (lauroyl).
An N-acetyl-alpha-D-glucosaminide in which the anomeric hydroxy hydrogen is replaced by a 4-nitrophenyl group.
A beta-D-galactopyranosyl diglyceride that consists of 2,3-diacyl-sn-glycerol having dodecanoyl as the acyl groups and the beta-D-galactopyranosyl residue attached at position 1.
An N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminide in which the anomeric hydroxy hydrogen is replaced by a 4-nitrophenyl group.
An L-proline derivative obtained by replacement of the amino hydrogen by a methyl group.
A mycolate ester formed by esterification of (2R)-2-{(1R)-1-hydroxy-15-[2-(20-methoxy-21-methylnonatriacontyl)cyclopropyl]pentadecyl}hexacosanoic acid with the 1-OH of glycerol.
A racemate comprising equimolar amounts of D- and L-methionine 2-naphthylamide.
A glycine derivative that is the amide obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of glycine with the amino group of 2-naphthylamine.
A mycolate ester formed by esterification of (2R)-2-{(1R)-1-hydroxy-15-[2-(20-methoxy-21-methylnonatriacontyl)cyclopropyl]pentadecyl}hexacosanoic acid with the 6-OH of D-glucose.
An L-alanine derivative that is the amide obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of L-alanine with the amino group of 2-naphthylamine.
An L-arginine derivative that is the amide obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of L-arginine with the amino group of 2-naphthylamine.
An L-asparagine derivative that is the amide obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of L-asparagine with the amino group of 2-naphthylamine.

A sulfoglycolipid in which alpha,alpha-trehalose, sulfated at the 2'-position, is acylated at the 2-position with palmitic acid, and at the 3-position with (2S,4S,6S,8S)-2,4,6,8-tetramethyltriacontanoic acid.
A dipeptide obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of L-phenylalanine with the amino group of L-glutamine.
An acetylenic compound that is propynoic acid in which the acetylenic hydrogen is replaced by a phenyl group.
A sulfone resulting from the oxidation of the sulfur atom of dibenzothiophene.

A glycohexaosylceramide having a beta-D-Gal-(1->4)-beta-D-GlcNAc-(1->3)-beta-D-Gal-(1->4)-beta-D-GlcNAc-(1->3)-beta-D-Gal-(1->4)-beta-D-Glc component attached to the primary hydroxy function of a ceramide with undefined sphingoid base and fatty acyl chain.

A glycoheptaosylceramide having a beta-D-Gal-(1->4)-beta-D-GlcNAc-(1->3)-beta-D-Gal-(1->4)-[alpha-L-Fuc-(1->3)]-beta-D-GlcNAc-(1->3)-beta-D-Gal-(1->4)-beta-D-Glc component attached to the primary hydroxy function of a ceramide with undefined sphingoid base and fatty acyl chain.
A glycolipid that consists of an alpha-D-galactosyl-(1->6)-beta-D-galactosyl residue attached at O-3 of glycerol, with either O-1 or O-2 acylated by a dodecanoyl group.
An indole alkaloid that is sarpagan bearing hydroxy groups at positions 10 and 17.

A glycoheptaosylceramide having a beta-D-Gal-(1->4)-[alpha-L-Fuc-(1->3)]-beta-D-GlcNAc-(1->3)-beta-D-Gal-(1->4)-beta-D-GlcNAc-(1->3)-beta-D-Gal-(1->4)-beta-D-Glc component attached to the primary hydroxy function of a ceramide with undefined sphingoid base and fatty acyl chain.
A 2-enoyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of 2-methylhexenoic acid.
An S-(5-deoxy-D-ribos-5-yl)-L-homocysteine in which the anomeric centre has beta-configuration.
An EC 4.6.* (P-O lyase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of enzyme adenylate cyclase (EC 4.6.1.1).

A phosphatidylinositol mannoside having on a myo-inositol ring a phosphatidyl moiety (carrying palmitoyl and 10-methyloctadecanoyl groups) at the 1-position, an alpha-D-mannosyl residue at the 2-position, a palmitoyl group at the 5-position and a 6-O-palmitoyl-alpha-D-mannosyl group at the 6-position.

An anionic phospholipid that is the conjugate base of 2-O-alpha-D-mannosyl-1-O-{1-O-[(10S)-10-methyloctadecanoyl]-2-O-palmitoyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphono}-5-O-palmitoyl-6-O-(6-O-palmitoyl-alpha-D-mannosyl)-1D-myo-inositol, obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate group.

An organic sodium salt that is the monosodium salt of 2-O-alpha-D-mannosyl-1-O-{1-O-[(10S)-10-methyloctadecanoyl]-2-O-palmitoyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphono}-5-O-palmitoyl-6-O-(6-O-palmitoyl-alpha-D-mannosyl)-1D-myo-inositol.
A member of the class of carbazoles that is 2,3,4,9-tetrahydro-1H-carbazole  which is substituted at position 1 by an aminocarbohyl group and at position 6 by a chlorine.
